#week-title("Three", "Evaporation, Salt Recovery & First Cohobation")

=== Core Teaching

Having produced the first dissolved mineral fraction in Week 2, the student
now continues the Via Humida cycle through evaporation, salt recovery, and
the first cohobation — completing one full cycle of the mineral spagyric.

*Evaporation.* The filtered mineral solution is placed in a shallow glass dish
or evaporating dish and warmed on a water bath. The water and volatile acid
fraction evaporate, concentrating and eventually crystallising the dissolved
mineral salts. This must be done gently — too high a temperature decomposes
the mineral salt compounds and destroys the preparation's quality.

The crystals that form during evaporation are not merely chemical curiosities.
They are the mineral's Salt principle concentrated and separated from its
Mercury (the water) and Sulphur (the acid medium that carried it into solution).
They carry the specific "signature" of the mineral in a concentrated, accessible
form.

*Observing crystallisation.* Different minerals produce dramatically different
crystal forms:
- *Iron acetate:* Yellow-brown to dark reddish crystals; hygroscopic
- *Copper acetate:* Deep blue-green crystals (verdigris character); one of the
  most beautiful mineral salts
- *Antimony fraction:* Pale yellowish residue; less distinctly crystalline

Photograph each stage of crystallisation. The crystal form is itself diagnostic
and was used by the tradition as a confirmatory sign of what the mineral's nature
truly is.

*First cohobation.* Once the crystal salt has been fully recovered and dried
gently (water bath, no higher than 80°C), it is placed back in the flask. A
fresh quantity of the acid medium is poured over it. This is the first
cohobation of the mineral salt — the return of the medium (carrying the
volatile fraction) to the fixed mineral salt, in direct analogy with the Year
One plant cohobation.

Observe: does the crystal salt dissolve readily in the fresh medium? Does
the colour of the new solution differ from the first dissolution? These
differences are significant and diagnostic.

=== Topics This Week

- Evaporation at the mineral level: gentle concentration on water bath
- Observing and photographing mineral crystallisation
- Crystal form as diagnostic of mineral character
- The first mineral cohobation: returning the medium to the salt

#inner-work[
  *The Crystal as Body*

  The mineral crystal is the Salt principle made most purely visible: the fixed,
  structured, geometric body in which the mineral's character is expressed with
  perfect regularity. Unlike a plant ash (amorphous) or a metal (dense,
  continuous), the crystal displays its internal structure openly in its external
  form.

  Sit with the crystals recovered from your evaporation for ten minutes. Attend
  to their geometry, their colour, the quality of light they transmit or reflect.
  What does the mineral's crystal body reveal about its character that the dissolved
  solution did not?
]

